gestures given an afterlife with the help of others. She looks at Louise Erdrich’s and Sherman Alexie’s user-amended captivity narratives; nontragic sequels to Moby-Dick by C. L. R. James, Frank Stella, and Amitav Ghosh; induced forms of Irishness in Henry James, Colm Tóibín, W. B. Yeats, and Gish Jen; and the experimentations afforded by a blurry Islam in works by Henri Matisse, James Joyce, Ezra Pound, and Langston Hughes. Celebrating literature’s durability as an assisted outcome, Weak Planet gives us new ways to think about our collective future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature, Moderny20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature, Moderny21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aassisted survival.  acaptivity narrative.  aclimate change.  acollateral resilience.  acrowd-sourced authorship.  amediating network.  anon-tragic sequels.  apastoral.  asubjunctive agency.  atragedy.1 aAlexie, Sherman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowles, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDilute Melville, Amitav Ghosh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErdrich, Louise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHughes, Langston, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJames, C. L. R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJames, Henry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJen, Gish, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoyce, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatisse, Henri